{
  "texts": [
    "In terms of normalization, Batch Normalization (BatchNorm) is extensively used to normalize each layer's inputs by computing the mean and variance across mini batches, reducing internal covariate shift and quickening convergence.",
    "Layer Normalization (LayerNorm) broadens this method by normalizing across all characteristics individually for each training sample, which has advantages in circumstances with changing batch sizes.",
    "GminDmaxV(D, G) = Ex ∼ pdata(x)[lodD(x)] + Ez ∼ pz(z) log(1 -D(G(z)))d = d -a∇ dJ( d) g = g -a∇ gJ( g)Group Normalization (GroupNorm) broadens these approaches by normalizing within small groups, making it useful when batch sizes are restricted.",
    "Regularization techniques, such as Dropout, are important for avoiding overfitting.",
    "During training, dropout randomly turns a proportion of input units to zero, pushing the network to rely on a variety of paths and limiting cell coadaptation."
  ]
}